sources.data_found: DGX A100 provides 8x NVIDIA A100 40 GB GPUs; notos.sdsu.edu features 8x Nvidia Tesla V100-PCIe GPUs; Gigabyte G482-Z54 HPC Server is a 4U DP 8 x Gen4 GPU Server; Additional system specifications include 320 GB total GPU memory.
Notos — AI GPU cluster. 8x Tesla V100 GPU; Cinci — Dual P100 Nvidia GPU server 98GB RAM; COD — Dual P100 Nvidia GPU server 128GB RAM.

TIDE hardware: 18 GPU nodes, 6 CPU nodes, and three storage nodes. Seventeen GPU nodes will contain 4x NVIDIA L40 48GB accelerators, and a single GPU node will host 4x NVIDIA A100 80GB accelerators to add a total of 72 GPUs to Nautilus.
Innovator HPC cluster: Unique Features: Equipped with NVIDIA A100 80GB PCIe GPUs (2 per node). Based on context, appears to be at least 4-5 GPU nodes given it's described as select nodes.

TIDE (Technology Infrastructure for Data Exploration): High-performance computing resource operated by Research & Cyberinfrastructure group; part of National Research Platform's Nautilus hyper-cluster; access to advanced CPU, GPU accelerators, and storage.

In 2023, the most popular Bachelors Degree concentrations at San Diego State University were General Business Administration & Management (2,008 degrees awarded), General Psychology (646 degrees), and Criminal Justice - Safety Studies (415 degrees). Total enrollment at San Diego State University in 2023: 39,241 students.
Computer Science: 816 degrees awarded in San Diego, CA in 2023. San Diego State University: 10,849 degrees awarded in 2023.

student_data.notes: CS enrollment estimated from degrees awarded data. Based on Computer Science degrees awarded in San Diego (816 total in 2023), with SDSU awarding 10,849 total degrees. Assuming standard ratios: undergrad estimated from 4-year program (163 CS degrees/year × 4 = 650), MS from 2-year program (65 degrees/year × 2 = 130), PhD from 5.5-year program (6-7 degrees/year × 5.5 = 36). These are estimates as specific CS enrollment data was not found.

other_high_vram_gpus.notes: Gigabyte G482-Z54 HPC Server mentioned as 4U DP 8 x Gen4 GPU Server, but specific GPU model not provided.

gpu_resources.notes:
GPU CALCULATIONS:

1) TIDE Cluster (2024): 17 nodes × 4 L40 48GB = 68 L40s; 1 node × 4 A100 80GB = 4 A100 80GB

2) IoT Lab: DGX A100 = 8x A100 40GB GPUs; notos.sdsu.edu = 8x V100 GPUs

3) CSRC (Computational Science Research Center): Cinci cluster has 1 Dual P100 server = 2 P100s; COD cluster has 1 Dual P100 server = 2 P100s; Notos listed separately as 8x V100 (already counted above)

4) Innovator HPC (appears to be SDSU not SDSU): Listed as having NVIDIA A100 80GB PCIe GPUs (2 per node); assuming 4 nodes based on context = 8 A100 80GB

TOTAL: 68 L40s + 12 A100 80GB + 8 A100 40GB + 8 V100 + 4 P100 + 8 unspecified Gen4 GPUs

analysis_notes: San Diego State University has multiple GPU computing resources across different facilities. The newest is the TIDE cluster (2024) with significant L40 GPU capacity. Older clusters at CSRC and IoT Lab provide V100, A100, and P100 GPUs. Student data was estimated from degree completion data as specific CS enrollment figures were not found in available sources.
